<p>Greenland’s government says it cannot accept being taken over by the United States “under any circumstances,” after President Trump renewed calls for U.S. control of the Danish autonomous territory, citing security concerns and its strategic location in the Arctic. In response to the rhetoric, Greenland and NATO signaled plans to strengthen Arctic security and defense coordination around the island. The situation is raising fresh questions about how NATO’s mutual-defense rules would work if one member threatened another member’s territory, and about the political cohesion of the alliance more broadly.</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/AltBrKKO4mb36N95QxVWkLiOFyVVhEUX50oo7xo6NGy4_J08W4xq9ns1-zs6kt8vj20c2KJuxZw-B8AMzFy9-0zMa5JfA5Uv8EfaQwoL6nXV' alt='A Greenlandic flag flutters in Copenhagen, Denmark on January 8, 2026. — Reuters/File' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Congress steps in: A bipartisan U.S. delegation led by Sen. Chris Coons plans to travel to Copenhagen on Friday and Saturday to meet Danish and Greenlandic officials, as some lawmakers discuss legislation aimed at limiting the President’s ability to attempt a seizure of Greenland.</li><li>EU warning: The EU’s defense and space commissioner said a U.S. military takeover of Greenland would effectively mean the end of NATO, while also saying the EU could help provide Greenland’s security if Denmark asked.</li><li>Article 5 focus: NATO’s core rule—Article 5—treats an attack on one member as an attack on all, a design meant to deter conflict but now central to public debate as allies consider hypothetical intra-alliance coercion scenarios.</li><li>Alliance strain risk: Analysts cited in Canadian coverage argue that any attempt by the United States to annex an ally’s territory could split NATO members over how to respond and set a precedent that undermines the alliance’s credibility.</li><li>Local security role: Greenland has argued its defense should sit clearly within NATO’s framework, aligning the island’s security posture with existing allied structures rather than bilateral pressure.</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Government of Greenland: Greenland’s leadership rejects any U.S. takeover and argues the territory’s security should be handled through NATO defense arrangements rather than annexation. (<a href='http://www.euronews.com/2026/01/12/greenland-and-nato-vow-to-boost-arctic-security-after-trumps-annexation-threats'>Euronews</a>)</li><li>President Donald Trump (United States): President Trump says the United States needs control of Greenland for national security, arguing that a U.S. military presence there is insufficient and that ownership would prevent Russia or China from gaining influence. (<a href='https://www.dawn.com/news/1966736/us-lawmakers-plan-denmark-visit-as-trump-threatens-greenland-takeover'>Dawn</a>)</li><li>Denmark (Kingdom of Denmark): Danish and Greenlandic officials maintain that Greenland is not for sale, as Copenhagen prepares discussions with U.S. counterparts amid the renewed pressure. (<a href='https://www.dawn.com/news/1966736/us-lawmakers-plan-denmark-visit-as-trump-threatens-greenland-takeover'>Dawn</a>)</li><li>U.S. Congress (bipartisan lawmakers): A bipartisan group of U.S. senators says Congress should support allies and respect Danish and Greenlandic sovereignty, while criticizing takeover threats as harmful to NATO unity. (<a href='https://www.cbsnews.com/news/congress-visits-denmark-trump-greenland-threats/'>CBS News</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.reddit.com/r/inthenews/comments/1qb2cga/greenland_says_it_cannot_accept_us_takeover_under/'>Greenland says it cannot accept US takeover ‘under any circumstances’</a> - reddit.com</li><li><a href='https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/article-nato-greenland-trump-threat-eu-europe-security/'>Trump’s Greenland aggression poses unforeseen threat to NATO alliance</a> - theglobeandmail.com</li><li><a href='http://www.euronews.com/2026/01/12/gre